The US Constitution's first amendment establishes separation of church and state, but court decisions have caused confusion.
The Supreme Court is reviewing the legality of displaying the Ten Commandments in public spaces.
Justices debated the issue, with Scalia supporting the displays as a symbol of government authority from God.
Challenges arose in Texas and Kentucky, questioning the constitutionality of religious exhibits.
Arguments focused on whether the displays violate the First Amendment.
Supporters claim the Commandments have historical significance in law.
The case aims to clarify government endorsement of religion and the secular nature of such displays.
